IWDS — Interactive World Direction System

Architecture Proposal v0.2

Pantheon Systems Research Draft

⸻

Abstract

The Interactive World Direction System (IWDS) proposes a unified runtime architecture that combines generative world models, real-time simulation engines, and conversational director agents into a persistent interactive environment.

Unlike conventional generative AI pipelines that produce static artifacts (images or videos), IWDS maintains a continuous world state that users can enter, modify, and direct through natural language.

The architecture consists of four cooperating layers:
	1.	Generative World Engine
	2.	Neural–Spatial Bridge (NSB)
	3.	Real-Time Simulation Runtime
	4.	Conversational Director Agent

Together these components form a closed loop:

generate → translate → simulate → direct → regenerate

This document defines the IWDS architecture, its translation layer (NSB), Pantheon integration, and major technical challenges.

⸻

1. Motivation

Current systems occupy three separate domains:

Generative AI systems

Examples: text-to-image or text-to-video.

Strengths:
	•	rapid content generation

Limitations:
	•	no persistent world state
	•	outputs are static artifacts

Game engines

Examples: modern real-time simulation frameworks.

Strengths:
	•	persistent environments
	•	physics and interaction

Limitations:
	•	require manual asset creation
	•	complex technical interfaces

Conversational AI agents

Examples: large language models.

Strengths:
	•	interpret natural language intent

Limitations:
	•	lack operational world models

