⸻

3. Neural–Spatial Bridge (NSB)

Purpose

The Neural–Spatial Bridge translates generative neural outputs into explicit spatial structures usable by the runtime simulation.

Generative models operate in latent pattern space, while simulation engines require explicit geometry and physics objects.

The bridge preserves object identity and operational meaning across this translation.

⸻

Translation Principle

A world object is considered successfully bridged when its load-bearing meaning survives conversion across substrates.

Example:

Representation	Form
Language	“Castle on a hill”
Neural	latent pattern field
Spatial	mesh + collider + navmesh
Perceptual	rendered fortress

The NSB ensures that the same world object persists across these representations.

⸻

4. NSB Translation Pipeline

When a command is issued, the bridge performs a multi-stage compilation.

Stage 1 — Intent Extraction

User command:

“Place a ruined stone castle on the hill with a courtyard.”

Converted into a structured Semantic Object Specification (SOS).

object_class: castle
material: stone
condition: ruined
location: hill_top
features: courtyard
affordances: enterable, traversable


⸻

Stage 2 — Invariant Binding

System identifies constraints that must remain true.

Examples:
	•	object must remain traversable
	•	location must remain hill-top
	•	courtyard must exist

These invariants are enforced later by Pantheon modules.

⸻

Stage 3 — Neural Generation

The generative engine produces candidate structures.

Possible formats include:
	•	implicit geometry fields
	•	neural radiance fields
	•	gaussian splat representations
	•	asset templates

These are packaged as Neural Representation Packets (NRP).

⸻

Stage 4 — Spatial Compilation

The bridge converts neural representations into runtime assets.

Generated components include:
	•	mesh geometry
	•	collision hulls
	•	navigation meshes
	•	physics parameters
	•	interaction anchors

These form Spatial Runtime Objects (SRO).

Example structure:

SRO {
  uuid
  mesh_ref
  collider_ref
  navmesh_ref
  transform
  semantic_tags
}


⸻

Stage 5 — Consistency Verification

Pantheon systems validate the object.

System	Role
Spider	scene graph integrity
Mirror	invariant validation
Hound	anomaly detection

Checks include:
	•	topology conflicts
	•	physics violations
	•	identity collisions
	•	navigation breaks

⸻

Stage 6 — Runtime Commit

Validated objects are inserted into the simulation runtime.

Operations include:
	•	UUID assignment
	•	scene graph insertion
	•	navigation recalculation
	•	event ledger logging

The object becomes part of the persistent world.

⸻

5. Reverse Translation (Spatial → Neural)

The NSB also operates in reverse.

Simulation runtimes may hold coarse spatial data, while neural systems provide perceptual richness.

Pipeline:

Spatial Runtime State
↓
Neural Enhancement
↓
Rendered Output

Enhancement may include:
	•	texture detail
	•	lighting refinement
	•	atmospheric effects
	•	cinematic motion

⸻

6. Operating Modes

The bridge supports three operational modes.

Mode I — Asset Synthesis

Neural models generate explicit assets.

Use cases:
	•	buildings
	•	characters
	•	terrain

Advantage:
	•	persistent interactable objects

Cost:
	•	higher computation

⸻

Mode II — Neural Overlay

Runtime holds simplified geometry while neural systems refine visuals.

Use cases:
	•	lighting
	•	atmosphere
	•	style changes

Advantage:
	•	faster updates

⸻

Mode III — Hybrid Mode

Default configuration.

Persistent structures are spatial assets while neural systems supply high-frequency detail.

Example:

Component	Representation
castle walls	runtime mesh
fog and lighting	neural overlay
surface detail	neural refinement


